Remaining Useful Life Est= imation Using Convolutional Neural Network

<= p class=3D"add_margin_5">This example uses:

  • Predictive Maintenance ToolboxPredictive = Maintenance Toolbox
  • Deep Learning ToolboxDeep Learning Toolbox

This example shows = how to predict the remaining useful life (RUL) of engines by using deep con= volutional neural networks (CNNs) [1]. The advantage of a deep learning approach is that you do not nee= d manual feature extraction or feature selection for your model to predict = RUL. Furthermore, you do not need prior knowledge of machine health prognos= tics or signal processing to develop a deep learning based RUL prediction m= odel.

Download Data Set

This example uses= the Turbofan Engine Degradation Simulation data set [1]. The data set is in ZIP file format, and conta= ins run-to-failure time-series data for four different sets (namely FD001, = FD002, FD003, and FD004) simulated under different combinations of operatio= nal conditions and fault modes.

This example uses only the FD001 data= set, which is further divided into training and test subsets. The training= subset contains simulated time series data for 100 engines. Each engine ha= s several sensors whose values are recorded at a given instance in a contin= uous process. Hence, the sequence of recorded data varies in length and cor= responds to a full run-to-failure (RTF) instance. The test subset contains = 100 partial sequences and corresponding values of the remaining useful life= at the end of each sequence.

Create a directory to store the Turbofa= n Engine Degradation Simulation data set.

  • Copy openExample Command
    Paste command in MATLAB to = download and open example files

  • Open in MA= TLAB Online
dataFolder =3D "data";
if ~exist(dataFolder,'dir')
    mkdir(dataFolder);
end

Download= and extract the Turbofan Engine Degradation Simulation data set.

    <= li class=3D"copy_code_block">

mulationData.zip");

The data folder now co= ntains text files with 26 columns of numbers, separated by spaces. Each row= is a snapshot of data taken during a single operational cycle, and each co= lumn represents a different variable:

    Column 1 =E2=80=94 Unit number

  • Column 2 =E2=80=94 Tim= estamp

  • Columns 3=E2=80=935 =E2=80=94 Operational settings

  • Columns 6=E2=80=9326 =E2=80=94 Sensor measurements 1=E2=80= =9321

Remove Features with Less Variability

Fea= tures that remain constant for all time steps can negatively impact the tra= ining. Use the prognosability funct= ion to measure the variability of features at failure.

  • Copy openExample Command
    Paste command = in MATLAB to download and open example files

  • Open in MATLAB Online
    • prog =3D prognosability(r=
awTrain.X,"timeStamp");

    For some features, prognosability is equal to zero or NaN. Disc= ard these features.

      • <= li role=3D"separator" aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"divider">

    • Copy ope= nExample Command
      Paste command in MATLAB to download and open exa= mple files

    • Open in MATLAB Online
      • <= /ul>
    idxToRemove =3D prog.Variables=3D=3D0 | isnan(prog.Variables=
);
featToRetain =3D prog.Properties.VariableNames(~idxToRemove);
for i =3D 1:height(rawTrain)
    rawTrain.X{i} =3D rawTrain.X{i}{:,featToRetain};
end

    Normalize Training Predictors

    Normal= ize the training predictors to have zero mean and unit variance.

    • <= span class=3D"icon-webinar"> Copy openExample Command
      Past= e command in MATLAB to download and open example files

    • Open in MATLAB Online
    [~,Xmu,Xsigma] =
=3D zscore(vertcat(rawTrain.X{:}));
preTrain =3D table();
for i =3D 1:numel(rawTrain.X)
    preTrain.X{i} =3D (rawTrain.X{i} - Xmu) ./ Xsigma;
end

    Clip Responses

    The response data rep= resents the RUL value over life for each engine and is based individual eng= ine lifetime. The sequence assumes a linear degradation from the time of th= e initial measurement to the time of engine failure.

    In order for net= work to focus on the part of the data where engines are more likely to fail= (end of the engine's life), clip the responses at the threshold of 150. Cl= ipping the responses causes the network to treat instances with higher RUL = values as equal.

    • Copy ope= nExample Command
      Paste command in MATLAB to download and open exa= mple files

    • Open in MATLAB Online
      • <= /ul>
    rulThreshold =3D 150;
for i =3D 1:numel(rawTrain.Y)
    preTrain.Y{i} =3D min(rawTrain.Y{i},rulThreshold);
end

    This fig= ure shows the first observation and the corresponding response (RUL), which= is clipped at the threshold. The green overlay defines the clipping region= on both sensor amd RUL plots.

    Prepare Data for Padding

    This network supports input= data with varying sequence lengths. When passing data through the network,= the software pads, truncates, or splits sequences so that all the sequence= s in each mini-batch have the specified length.

    To minimize the amoun= t of padding added to the mini-batches, sort the training data by sequence = length. Then, choose a mini-batch size which divides the training data even= ly and reduces the amount of padding in the mini-batches.

    Sort the tr= aining data by sequence length.

    • Copy Code Block=

    • <= /span> Copy openExample Command
      Paste command in MATLAB to downlo= ad and open example files

    • Open in MATLAB= Online
    for i =
=3D 1:size(preTrain,1)
    preTrain.X{i} =3D preTrain.X{i}';    %Tra=
nspose training data to have features in the first dimension
    preTrain.Y{i} =3D preTrain.Y{i}';    %Tra=
nspose responses corresponding to the training data
    sequence =3D preTrain.X{i};
    sequenceLengths(i) =3D size(sequence,2);=20
end

[sequenceLengths,idx] =3D sort(sequenceLengths,'descend');
XTrain =3D preTrain.X(idx);
YTrain =3D preTrain.Y(idx);

    Network Architecture

    The deep co= nvolutional neural network architecture used for RUL estimation is describe= d in [1].

    Here, you p= rocess and sort the data in a sequence format, with the first dimension rep= resenting the number of selected features and the second dimension represen= ting the length of the time sequence. You bundle convolutional layers with = batch normalization layer followed by an activation layer (relu in this cas= e) and then stack the layers together for feature extraction. The fully con= nected layers are used at the end to get the final RUL value as output.

    =

    The selected network architecture applies a 1-D convolution along the ti= me sequence direction only. Therefore, the order of features does not impac= t the training and only trends in one feature at a time are considered.

    =

    Define the network architecture. Create a CNN that consists of five con= secutive sets of a convolution 1-d, batch normalization and, a relu layer, = with increasing filterSize and numFilters as the first two input arguments to convolution1dLayer, followed by a fully connected la= yer of size numHiddenUnits and a dropout lay= er with a dropout probability of 0.5. Since the network predicts the remain= ing useful life (RUL) of the turbofan engine, set n= umResponses to 1 in the second fully connected layer.

    To comp= ensate for the varying time-sequences in the training data, use Padding=3D"causal" as the Name-value pair input argumen= t in convolution1dLayer.

    • Copy openExample Command
      Paste = command in MATLAB to download and open example files

    • Open in MATLAB Online
    numFeatures =3D=
 size(XTrain{1},1);
numHiddenUnits =3D 100;
numResponses =3D 1;

layers =3D [
    sequenceInputLayer(numFeatures)
    convolution1dLayer(5,32,Padding=3D"causal=
")
    batchNormalizationLayer
    reluLayer()
    convolution1dLayer(7,64,Padding=3D"causal=
")
    batchNormalizationLayer
    reluLayer()
    convolution1dLayer(11,128,Padding=3D"caus=
al")
    batchNormalizationLayer
    reluLayer()
    convolution1dLayer(13,256,Padding=3D"caus=
al")
    batchNormalizationLayer
    reluLayer()
    convolution1dLayer(15,512,Padding=3D"caus=
al")
    batchNormalizationLayer
    reluLayer()
    fullyConnectedLayer(numHiddenUnits)
    reluLayer()
    dropoutLayer(0.5)
    fullyConnectedLayer(numResponses)];

    Train Network

    Specify = trai= ningOptions (Deep Learning Toolbox). Train for 40 epochs with min= ibatches of size 16 using the Adam optimizer. Set L= earnRateSchedule to piecewise. Specify the learning rate as 0.01. To pr= event the gradients from exploding, set the gradient threshold to 1. To kee= p the sequences sorted by length, set 'Shuffle' to 'never'. Turn on the training progres= s plot and also set the Metrics to 'rmse' to view the RMSE plot. Set the InputDataFormats as CTB beca= use the training data contains features in the first dimension, time-series= sequence in the second dimension, and the batches of the data in the third= dimension. Turn off the command window output (Ver= bose).

      • <= li role=3D"separator" aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"divider">

    • Copy ope= nExample Command
      Paste command in MATLAB to download and open exa= mple files

    • Open in MATLAB Online
      • = 
    maxEpochs =3D 40;
miniBatchSize =3D 16;

options =3D trainingOptions('adam',...
    LearnRateSchedule=3D'piecewise',...
    MaxEpochs=3DmaxEpochs,...
    MiniBatchSize=3DminiBatchSize,...
    InitialLearnRate=3D0.01,...
    GradientThreshold=3D1,...
    Shuffle=3D'never',...
    Plots=3D'training-progress',...
    Metrics=3D'rmse',...
    InputDataFormats=3D'CTB',...
    Verbose=3D0);

    Train the network using trainnet and specify the loss function as mean squa= red error (mse). This should take about 1-2 minutes.

  • Copy openExample Command
    Paste comm= and in MATLAB to download and open example files

  • Open in MATLAB Online
    • net =3D trainnet(XTr=
ain,YTrain,layers,"mse",options);

    Plot the layer graph of the network to visualize the = underlying network architecture.

      Paste command in MATLAB to downl= oad and open example files

    figure;
plot(net)

    Test Network

    The= test data contains 100 partial sequences and corresponding values of the r= emaining useful life at the end of each sequence.

  • Copy openExample Command
    Paste command = in MATLAB to download and open example files

  • Open in MATLAB Online
    • filenameTestPredictors =
=3D fullfile(dataFolder,'test_FD001.txt');
filenameTestResponses =3D fullfile(dataFolder,'RUL_FD001.txt');
dataTest =3D localLoadData(filenameTestPredictors,filenameTestResponses);

    Prepare the test data set for predictions by perfo= rming the same preprocessing steps you use to prepare the training data set= .

    Get

    • Copy openExample C= ommand
      Paste command in MATLAB to download and open example files=

    • Open in MATLAB Online
    for i =3D 1:numel(dataTest.X)
    dataTest.X{i} =3D dataTest.X{i}{:,featToRetain};
    dataTest.X{i} =3D (dataTest.X{i} - Xmu) ./ Xsigma;
    dataTest.Y{i} =3D min(dataTest.Y{i},rulThreshold);
end

    Create a= table for storing the predicted response (YPred) along with the true response (Y). Make= predictions on the test data using minibatchpredic= t. To prevent the function from adding padding to the test data, spe= cify the mini-batch size as 1 to get RUL value for each observation in the = test data. Set InputDataFormats as CTB because the test data is also in the same format = as the training data.

    • C= opy openExample Command
      Paste command in MATLAB to download and o= pen example files

    • Open in MATLAB Online<= /a>
    predictions =3D table(Size=3D[height(dataTest) 2],V=
ariableTypes=3D["cell","cell"],VariableNames=3D["Y","YPred"]);

for i=3D1:height(dataTest)
    unit =3D dataTest.X{i}';  =20
    predictions.Y{i} =3D dataTest.Y{i}';
    predictions.YPred{i} =3D minibatchpredict(net,unit,MiniBatchSize=3D1,In=
putDataFormats=3D'CTB');
end

    Performance Metrics

    Compute the root= mean squared error (RMSE) across all time cycles of the test sequences to = analyze how well the network performs on the test data.

    • Copy openExample Command
      Paste com= mand in MATLAB to download and open example files

    • Open in MATLAB Online
    for i =3D 1:size(predictions,1)
    predictions.RMSE(i) =3D sqrt(mean((predictions.Y{i} - predictions.YPred=
{i}).^2));
end

    Create a= histogram to visualize the distribution of RMSE values across all test eng= ines.

    <= button type=3D"button" class=3D"btn btn-default dropdown-toggle" data-toggl= e=3D"dropdown" aria-haspopup=3D"true" aria-expanded=3D"false"> Get

    • Copy openExample C= ommand
      Paste command in MATLAB to download and open example files=

    • Open in MATLAB Online
    figure;
histogram(predictions.RMSE,NumBins=3D10);
title("RMSE ( Mean: " + round(mean(pre=
dictions.RMSE),2) + " , StDev: " + rou=
nd(std(predictions.RMSE),2) + " )");
ylabel('Frequency');
xlabel('RMSE');
    =

    Additionally, to see how the network predictor perf= orms throughout the given sequence of data in the test engines, use the localLambdaPlot function to plot the predicted = RUL against the true RUL of a random test engine.

  • Copy openExample Command
    Paste command = in MATLAB to download and open example files

  • Open in MATLAB Online
    • figure;
localLambdaPlot(predictions,"random");=

    The result shows that the = CNN deep learning architecture for estimating RUL of the turbo engine data = is a viable approach to predict RUL. The RMSE values at all timestamps indi= cates that the network can perform well towards the end of the given test s= equence data. Therefore, having a brief history of the sensor data is impor= tant when trying to predict RUL.

    Helper Functions

    Load Data Function

    This function loads run-to-failure data from the provided te= xt file and groups time-series data and its corresponding RUL values in a t= able as predictors and responses.

    • Copy openExample Command
      Paste command in MATLAB to = download and open example files

    • Open in M= ATLAB Online
    function=
 data =3D localLoadData(filenamePredictors,varargin)

if isempty(varargin)
    filenameResponses =3D [];=20
else
    filenameResponses =3D varargin{:};
end

%% Load the text file as a table
rawData =3D readtable(filenamePredictors);

% Add variable names to the table
VarNames =3D {...
    'id', 'timeStamp', 'op_setting_1', =
'op_setting_2', 'op_setting_3', ...
    'sensor_1', 'sensor_2', 'sensor_3',=
 'sensor_4', 'sensor_5', ...
    'sensor_6', 'sensor_7', 'sensor_8',=
 'sensor_9', 'sensor_10', ...
    'sensor_11', 'sensor_12', 'sensor_13', 'sensor_14', 'sensor_15', ...
    'sensor_16', 'sensor_17', 'sensor_18', 'sensor_19', 'sensor_20', ...
    'sensor_21'};
rawData.Properties.VariableNames =3D VarNames;

if ~isempty(filenameResponses)
    RULTest =3D readmatrix(filenameResponses);
end

% Split the signals for each unit ID
IDs =3D rawData{:,1};
nID =3D unique(IDs);
numObservations =3D numel(nID);

% Initialize a table for storing data
data =3D table(Size=3D[numObservations 2],...=

    VariableTypes=3D{'cell','cell'},...
    VariableNames=3D{'X','Y'});

for i=3D1:numObservations
    idx =3D IDs =3D=3D nID(i);
    data.X{i} =3D rawData(idx,:);
    if isempty(filenameResponses)
        % Calculate RUL from time column for =
train data
        data.Y{i} =3D flipud(rawData.timeStamp(idx))-1;
    else
        % Use RUL values from filenameRespons=
es for test data
        sequenceLength =3D sum(idx);
        endRUL =3D RULTest(i);
        data.Y{i} =3D [endRUL+sequenceLength-1:-1:endRUL]'; %#ok<NBRAK> 
    end
end
end

    Lambda Plot function

    This helper function accepts the= predictions table and a lambdaCase argument, and plots the predicted RUL against the tr= ue RUL throughout its sequence (at every timestamp) for a visualization of = how the prediction changes with every timestamp. The second argument, lambdaCase, can be the test engine number or one = of a set of valid strings to find an engine number : "random", "best", "wor= st", or "average".

    • Copy o= penExample Command
      Paste command in MATLAB to download and open e= xample files

    • Open in MATLAB Online
    function localLambda=
Plot(predictions,lambdaCase)

if isnumeric(lambdaCase)
    idx =3D lambdaCase;
else
    switch lambdaCase
        case {"Random","random","r"}
            idx =3D randperm(height(predictions),1); % Randomly choose a test case to plot
        case {"Best","best","b"}
            idx =3D find(predictions.RMSE =3D=3D min(predictions.RMSE)); % Best case
        case {"Worst","worst","w"}
            idx =3D find(predictions.RMSE =3D=3D max(predictions.RMSE)); % Worst case
        case {"Average","average","a"}
            err =3D abs(predictions.RMSE-mean(predictions.RMSE));
            idx =3D find(err=3D=3Dmin(err),1);
    end
end
y =3D predictions.Y{idx};
yPred =3D predictions.YPred{idx};
x =3D 0:numel(y)-1;
plot(x,y,x,yPred)
legend("True RUL","Predicted RUL")
xlabel("Time stamp (Test data sequence)")
ylabel("RUL (Cycles)")

title("RUL for Test engine #"+idx+ " ("+lambdaCase+" case)")
end

    References=

    1. Li, Xiang, Qian Ding, and Jian-Qiao Sun. =E2=80=9CRemaining Us= eful Life Estimation in Prognostics Using Deep Convolution Neural Networks.= =E2=80=9D Reliability Engineering & System Safety 172 (April 2018): 1= =E2=80=9311. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ress.2017.11.021.
